<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911007-0001</DOCNO><DOCID>911007-0001.</DOCID><HL>   Hospital Firm Faces   U.S., State Inquiries   Into Alleged Fraud</HL><DATE>10/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B10</SO><CO>   NME</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)INSURANCE (INS)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)FLORIDA (FL)LOUISIANA (LA)NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Federal officials and five states, including New Jerseyand Texas, are conducting investigations into allegeddefrauding of health insurance companies by a network ofhospitals controlled by National Medical Enterprises Inc.,according to a report in yesterday's Newark Star-Ledger.   The newspaper said it &quot;learned that several major healthcarriers,&quot; including Prudential Insurance Co. of America andBlue Cross and Blue Shield of New Jersey &quot;have beensubpoenaed by federal authorities to produce records andother data concerning their dealings with,&quot; among others,Fair Oaks Hospital, a psychiatric institution in Summit, N.J.</LP><TEXT>   Fair Oaks is owned by Psychiatric Institutes of America, aunit of National Medical Enterprises, based in Santa Monica,Calif.   The Star Ledger, in a front-page story, also saidinvestigations were under way in Louisiana, Florida and astate in the Midwest; the paper didn't identify theMidwestern state. The newspaper's article cited &quot;sources&quot; whosaid the data requested relate to &quot;overbilling insurancecompanies, billings for services never provided or required,misdiagnosis of patients in order to maximize their insurancebenefits and similar tactics.&quot;   National Medical Enterprises' offices were closedyesterday, according to a taped message. Robert L. Krakower,an attorney with the Roseland, N.J., firm of Lowenstein,Sandler, Kohl, Fisher andamp; Boyland, which represents Fair Oaks,said, &quot;The state of New Jersey conducted a lengthyinvestigation which concluded with an agreement thatexpressly states there was no evidence of criminalwrongdoing. We believe any investigation would reach thissame conclusion.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>